[49m[38;5;10m+     1[0m:[38;5;10m[49m # Recipe 11.9: Care Coordination Assistant
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     2[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     3[0m:[38;5;10m[49m **Complexity:** Complex · **Phase:** Regulated · **Estimated Cost:** ~$3-12 per active member per month (depends on engagement frequency, channel mix, model choice, RAG depth, integration depth across providers and systems, and human-care-manager backstop overhead)
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     4[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     5[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     6[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     7[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ## The Problem
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     8[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     9[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret is 68. She has type 2 diabetes that has been reasonably controlled for fifteen years, congestive heart failure with an ejection fraction of about 35%, stage 3 chronic kidney disease, atrial fibrillation on apixaban, hypothyroidism, osteoarthritis in both knees, and (since last Thursday) a new diagnosis of early-stage breast cancer found on a routine screening mammogram. Her primary care physician (the one she has had for nine years and who knows her best) is at a small independent practice. Her cardiologist is at the academic medical center across town. Her nephrologist is at a different hospital system because that is where her PCP could get her in within three months when her creatinine started climbing in 2023. Her endocrinologist retired last year and the new one is at the academic medical center but uses a different clinic location than the cardiologist. The breast surgeon who is going to do the lumpectomy is at the academic medical center. The medical oncologist who will see her after the lumpectomy to decide on adjuvant therapy has not been chosen yet because the breast surgeon's office said they would refer once the pathology is back. The radiation oncologist will be assigned later. Margaret's husband died three years ago. Her two daughters live out of state.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    10[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    11[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In the next eight weeks, Margaret has the following appointments and tasks scheduled or pending: a pre-operative visit with her PCP to clear her for surgery (next Tuesday); pre-operative labs at a hospital lab her PCP's office sends them to (Wednesday); a pre-operative anesthesia consult at the academic medical center (Thursday afternoon, requires her to drive across town and find parking, which Margaret no longer particularly enjoys); a cardiology follow-up that was already scheduled before the cancer diagnosis (the following Monday, at the cardiologist's office, which her cardiologist's nurse-practitioner has now flagged as a "should-we-keep-or-reschedule given the surgery" question that nobody has answered); the lumpectomy (two weeks out, at the academic medical center); a post-operative visit with the breast surgeon (six days after surgery); a pathology-results discussion with the breast surgeon (about ten days after surgery); a referral to medical oncology that does not yet exist as an appointment; a referral to radiation oncology that does not yet exist as an appointment; a follow-up with her nephrologist that her nephrologist's office wants to schedule before the surgery because contrast and certain perioperative medications need her renal function reviewed; a follow-up with her endocrinologist about a recent A1c trend; her quarterly blood-thinner monitoring; her annual mammogram on the contralateral breast (which Margaret is now afraid to think about); a flu shot her PCP keeps reminding her about; the home blood-pressure cuff her cardiologist asked her to use; the home glucose log her endocrinologist wants; and the eight-week pulmonary-rehab program her PCP mentioned in passing two months ago that Margaret never got around to enrolling in.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    12[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    13[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret is also taking eleven medications (apixaban, metformin, semaglutide, bisoprolol, sacubitril-valsartan, furosemide, atorvastatin, levothyroxine, allopurinol, low-dose aspirin until her surgeon tells her otherwise, and a daily multivitamin), and she will be told to hold the apixaban for several days around her surgery, restart it on a specific schedule the breast surgeon's office and the cardiologist's office will need to agree on, hold the semaglutide for at least a week before surgery, possibly hold the metformin around contrast exposure depending on her renal function on the day, and stop the aspirin four days before surgery. Her surgeon's pre-op instructions and her cardiologist's pre-op instructions and her nephrologist's pre-op instructions arrive on three different patient-portal logins (because the surgeon and the nephrologist use the same EHR vendor but different tenant configurations, and the cardiologist uses a different EHR vendor entirely), in three different formats, with three different sets of phone numbers to call if she has questions. The instructions partially overlap and partially conflict. Margaret has a binder. The binder has been useful and is also full.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    14[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    15[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret's PCP, who is an excellent doctor and a thoughtful one, has thirty other patients on the schedule that day and a backlog of inbox messages from the previous evening. The PCP's care manager (the practice has one, shared across about twelve hundred patients) has Margaret on a list, but the list is long and Margaret has not, until recently, been the most acute patient on it. The breast surgeon's office has a navigator (who is excellent at her job and also covers about a hundred and forty active surgical patients). The academic medical center has a separate cancer-center-level navigator who will be assigned after the medical oncology referral lands. The cardiologist's office has its own care coordinator. The nephrologist's office has nobody. The endocrinologist's new practice has somebody whose role is not entirely clear. The insurer (which is a Medicare Advantage plan, not original Medicare) has a case manager who has reached out twice and whom Margaret has never called back because she does not understand who the woman is or what the call is about, and she is suspicious of unsolicited calls about her health from unknown numbers. None of these care managers and navigators talk to each other. They each have a sliver of Margaret's situation. They each have her best interests at heart. They are each operating with partial information.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    16[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    17[0m:[38;5;10m[49m In the next eight weeks, several specific things will happen, in approximately this order, that nobody currently in the system will catch in time to prevent:
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    18[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    19[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pre-operative anesthesia consult will identify that Margaret is on apixaban and will recommend holding it for a specific number of days; the cardiologist's office, when later asked, will recommend a slightly different schedule; the breast surgeon's office will default to its standard surgical-anticoagulation policy. The three recommendations will not be reconciled. Margaret will follow the one she remembers best, which is whichever one was on the printout she could find that morning.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    20[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    21[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pre-operative labs will be drawn at a hospital lab that does not, by default, route results to the cardiologist or the nephrologist; the surgeon's office will see them, but the cardiologist (who needs to see the BNP) and the nephrologist (who needs to see the creatinine) will not, until somebody asks specifically. The asking will not happen because nobody at the surgeon's office knows that the cardiologist and the nephrologist need to see them, because nobody told them.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    22[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    23[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The cardiology follow-up appointment that the nurse-practitioner flagged for reschedule-or-keep will sit unanswered for three days, then will be rescheduled to a date that conflicts with Margaret's pre-op anesthesia visit. Margaret will discover this on the morning of the conflict by looking at her phone calendar.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    24[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    25[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The pathology results will come back on a Friday afternoon. The breast surgeon's office will leave Margaret a voicemail on Saturday morning saying "we'd like to set up a time to discuss the results next week." Margaret will spend the weekend assuming the worst, because she is a reasonable person and pathology callbacks on Saturday mornings are not generally good news. The surgeon will call back on Tuesday and tell her, in fact, the news is generally good (negative margins, a small focus, hormone-receptor-positive, low Oncotype-prediction range, candidate for lumpectomy plus radiation plus endocrine therapy, no chemotherapy probably indicated). Margaret will not absorb most of this conversation because she has been waiting for three days and her hearing-on-the-phone is not what it was.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    26[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    27[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The medical oncology referral will be made by the surgeon's office two weeks after the pathology discussion (because that is when the surgeon's office's standard workflow processes the referral), to a medical oncologist at the academic medical center. The first available new-patient slot will be six weeks out. Margaret will not know that there is a different medical oncologist, also in-network, also at the academic medical center, with a fourteen-day wait, who would be a clinically-appropriate alternative; the surgeon's office does not maintain that list, and the central scheduling system does not surface it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    28[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    29[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The radiation oncology referral will be made even later, because the standard sequence is medical oncology first, even though in Margaret's case the radiation oncology consult could productively happen earlier in parallel.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    30[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    31[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The endocrinologist's office will, at some point in this window, receive lab results showing that Margaret's A1c has crept up by 0.3, partly due to the steroid she is on for her pulmonary-rehab-related inflammation issue (which she did not enroll in but did receive a steroid prescription for from a different visit in February), partly due to the increased anxiety, partly because perioperative stress matters. The endocrinologist's office will call to schedule a follow-up. The follow-up will be scheduled three months out, because the office does not know that Margaret is in the middle of a cancer surgery and that her diabetes management is going to be more reactive than usual for the next ninety days.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    32[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    33[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The nephrologist's office will receive Margaret's surgical labs, will note the creatinine has bumped slightly, will recommend holding the metformin around contrast and will recommend a specific perioperative-fluid plan; this recommendation will reach Margaret as a phone message that Margaret will half-listen to at 3 PM while trying to also pay her electric bill, and the recommendation will not reach the breast surgeon's office at all.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    34[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    35[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The Medicare Advantage plan's case manager will, in the meantime, send Margaret a letter about a "care management opportunity" in the form of a glossy brochure, which Margaret will throw away because it looks like an advertisement.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    36[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    37[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Margaret will get through this. Most patients in Margaret's situation do, by some combination of personal resourcefulness, a reasonably-functioning healthcare system, the goodwill of individual clinicians, and luck. Some do not. The ones who do not are not the ones with the worst clinical situations; they are the ones whose care became the most fragmented, whose handoffs failed in the worst sequences, whose questions waited the longest for answers, whose conflicting instructions resolved in the worst direction. Care fragmentation is not a clinical-quality problem; it is the clinical-quality problem, in any patient with more than two clinicians and more than one acute issue. The literature on it is depressing. <!-- TODO: verify; the literature on care fragmentation as a driver of adverse outcomes is extensive across hospital readmissions, medication errors, and quality-of-care measures; specific findings vary by population and study --> In one frame: care coordination is most of what good primary care is, and primary care has been losing capacity for fifteen years. In another frame: every health system promises care coordination and almost none deliver it at scale. In a third frame: the coordination problem has gotten harder, not easier, as care has become more specialized, as the number of clinicians involved in a typical complex case has grown, as the number of EHR systems and patient portals has multiplied, as the share of care delivered virtually has expanded, and as the share of care delivered outside the largest integrated systems has remained substantial. The patient is the only person in the picture with a complete view. The patient is also the person least equipped to maintain that view, especially when the patient is sick, frightened, on eleven medications, and managing this without a partner.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    38[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    39[0m:[38;5;10m[49m The thing this recipe is about is whether a conversational AI assistant, deployed carefully and integrated with the institution's care-management infrastructure, can be the connective tissue. Not a replacement for the human care manager, the navigator, the social worker, or the PCP. Not a substitute for the patient's relationships with the people who are supposed to know them. A tool, in the patient's hand, that knows enough of the picture to remind, to summarize, to flag conflicts, to surface the right phone number, to draft the question to ask at the next appointment, to escalate to a human when the situation calls for it. The patient still does the work, because the patient is the only person in a position to. The assistant makes the work do-able.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    40[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    41[0m:[38;5;10m[49m This is also one of the recipes in the chapter where the temptation to over-extend is most dangerous, because the patient population (high-touch, high-need, often elderly, often with limited support) is the population where the consequences of bot drift are most severe and the operational backstop is most expensive. The architectural pattern needs to be honest about what the bot can and cannot do, and the operational pattern needs to be honest about how much human care-management capacity has to sit behind it. Build this bot without the human backstop and the bot is unsafe; build this bot to replace the human care manager and the bot is unsafe in a different way; build this bot as a force-multiplier for an existing care-management infrastructure and the bot can meaningfully change patients' experience. The architectural decisions follow from that framing.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    42[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    43[0m:[38;5;10m[49m Let's get into it.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    44[0m:[38;5;10m[49m 
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+    45[0m:[38;5;10m[49m ---
